{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":36204,"record_hash":"sha256:b3e1104dcf04af2e946b024ad055cc7766564a0f9867a0691bff2137ab47af4d","timestamp":"2026-05-12T08:37:56.581Z","kind":"tool_call","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:custom_tool_call","role":null,"text":null,"tool_name":"apply_patch","tool_input":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 Active/agent-session-capture/session-association-risks.md\n+# Session Association Risks\n+\n+This note documents the brittle parts of connecting captured agent sessions to\n+branches, changes, commits, or pull requests. It is not an implementation plan.\n+Its job is to keep the risks visible before we choose a design.\n+\n+## What We Want\n+\n+The durable object is still the project-scoped agent session:\n+\n+```text\n+project\n+  gitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:*\n+```\n+\n+Future review or branch objects should reference those sessions:\n+\n+```text\n+<branch/change/commit/pr target>\n+  gitbutler:agent-sessions = set<session-key>\n+```\n+\n+The relationship should mean \"this session is relevant to this target\", not\n+\"this session uniquely generated this target\". That wording matters because the\n+real workflow is many-to-many:\n+\n+- one session can contribute to several branches or pull requests\n+- one branch or pull request can involve several sessions\n+- a session can be useful context even before any code exists\n+- a session can contain useful discussion even if no generated code is kept\n+\n+## Why Capture-Time Association Is Weak\n+\n+Associating a session with the current branch while capture runs is tempting,\n+but the capture moment has poor evidence about where the work will land.\n+\n+Ways this can go wrong:\n+\n+- The user starts on `main`, generates code, then creates or switches to the\n+  correct branch before committing.\n+- GitButler can have multiple active branches in one worktree, so \"current\n+  branch\" may not describe the destination of each hunk.\n+- The session may produce edits that are split into a feature branch and a\n+  bugfix branch.\n+- The session may only be planning or discussion, with no committed output yet.\n+- The user may discard the generated edits.\n+- The capture hook may run many times during a long session, before the user has\n+  decided what belongs where.\n+- Branch state is workspace context, not durable provenance.\n+\n+For those reasons, capture should continue to store project-scoped session data\n+and avoid inferred branch, change, commit, or PR ownership.\n+\n+## Why Commit-Time Association Is Better, But Still Brittle\n+\n+Commit and amend operations have more evidence because GitButler can see the\n+actual change being recorded. That still does not make the association obvious.\n+\n+Time is useful but insufficient:\n+\n+- A user can generate code, review it for hours, step away, and commit later.\n+- A long session can span unrelated tasks across hours or days.\n+- Several recent sessions may touch the same area of the project.\n+- A session can be captured or synced late, so \"recently captured\" and\n+  \"recently authored\" can differ.\n+\n+File overlap is useful but insufficient:\n+\n+- The agent may discuss files it does not edit.\n+- The user may manually edit generated code before committing.\n+- Tool calls and tool results may be redacted or slimmed, so they are not a\n+  complete edit trace.\n+- The user can copy code from an agent UI without a provider tool call that names\n+  the modified file.\n+- Multiple agents or multiple sessions may touch the same files.\n+\n+The safest first stance is that low-confidence evidence should not silently\n+create a relationship. False positives are more harmful than missing links\n+because they can mislead reviewers about how code was produced.\n+\n+## Whole Session Or Portion Of Session\n+\n+Associating an entire session is pragmatic and simple. It also works naturally\n+with the current project-scoped transcript model.\n+\n+The downside is noise:\n+\n+- a multi-day session may include unrelated work\n+- early planning may apply to one branch while later tool use applies to another\n+- a reviewer may only need a small window of the transcript\n+\n+Persisting transcript slices is more precise in theory, but brittle in practice.\n+The slice can become misleading after manual edits, squashes, moves, or later\n+conversation. A better early direction is to store the session relationship and\n+let future readers derive likely relevant windows from timestamps, files, tool\n+mentions, and user selection.\n+\n+## Mutation Lifecycle Risks\n+\n+Once relationships exist, they can drift when code is reshaped.\n+\n+Operations that can break or blur the relationship:\n+\n+- **Amend:** the same change may need to preserve old session links and add a\n+  new one if the amendment came from a later session.\n+- **Uncommit and recommit:** relationships can be orphaned, duplicated, or\n+  attached to the wrong new object if change identity is not preserved.\n+- **Split or move hunks:** one original association may need to be copied,\n+  divided, or dropped across multiple destinations.\n+- **Squash:** source session links should probably be unioned into the\n+  destination. Otherwise a large AI-generated change squashed into a small\n+  manual change can lose provenance if the destination change id wins.\n+- **Reorder or rebase:** commit ids change. Links attached only to commit ids\n+  will be fragile; durable change ids are a better anchor when available.\n+- **Branch rename, delete, or recreate:** branch-level links are convenient for\n+  views but weak as the primary durable relationship.\n+- **Undo and redo:** replayed operations can accidentally replay stale metadata\n+  changes or forget them entirely.\n+- **Plain Git operations outside GitButler:** commits, rebases, and squashes can\n+  bypass GitButler's association logic.\n+\n+The implementation risk is footprint. If every operation needs custom metadata\n+edge handling, one missed path creates silent provenance drift.\n+\n+## Data Model Implications\n+\n+The current direction still looks right:\n+\n+- keep transcript data on durable project sessions\n+- use many-to-many relationship sets from branch/change/commit/PR targets to\n+  session keys\n+- prefer change ids over branches as durable anchors when GitButler has them\n+- let branch and PR views union lower-level relationships instead of owning\n+  transcript copies\n+- keep stored relationships coarse until the UI and workflow prove where more\n+  precision is needed\n+\n+If relationship metadata is added later, it should earn its keep. Possible\n+fields are `method`, `confidence`, and `evidence`, but those should wait until\n+there is a concrete reader or UI that needs them.\n+\n+## Open Questions\n+\n+- Which signals are strong enough to create an automatic association?\n+- Should the commit UI ask the user to confirm suggested sessions?\n+- Should GitButler track an explicit \"active agent session\" during a workspace\n+  session?\n+- How should non-GitButler Git operations be represented, if at all?\n+- Should relationships be stored permanently, recomputed from evidence, or both?\n+- How much uncertainty should be shown to reviewers?\n+- What is the smallest centralized API that can keep association updates out of\n+  every individual mutation path?\n+\n+## Cautious Direction\n+\n+Do not infer association at capture time.\n+\n+When this feature moves beyond the POC, start with explicit relationships and\n+high-confidence GitButler commit or amend moments. Treat stored links as\n+\"relevant sessions\", not exact causality. Prefer one centralized relationship\n+operation over scattered set mutations across commit, amend, squash, move, undo,\n+and branch code paths.\n*** Update File: /Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 Active/agent-session-capture/future-use-cases.md\n@@\n Relationship keys can look like this:\n \n ```text\n <branch/change/commit target>\n   gitbutler:agent-sessions = set<session-key>\n@@\n - many sessions associated with one branch or review object\n - branch or commit associations being added after capture\n+\n+See [Session Association Risks](session-association-risks.md) for the brittle\n+parts of inferring and maintaining those relationships.\n \n ## POC Direction\n*** Update File: /Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 Active/agent-session-capture/gitmeta-data-model.md\n@@\n See [Future Use Cases](future-use-cases.md) for access patterns and product\n-motivation.\n+motivation, and [Session Association Risks](session-association-risks.md) for\n+why inferred relationships should stay cautious.\n \n ## Publication\n*** End Patch\n","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-12T08:37:56.581Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","status":"completed","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]","name":"apply_patch"}}}